>>35150239
As writers, we aim to please. It's hard-coded into the hobby by our very nature as social animals. We obtain fulfillment in those moments where our enjoyment in the act itself meets with satisfaction in the product. It's selfless to want to share that with people, despite how meek, reticent, shy, nervous, humble, (whichever applies) etc. we are as individuals. It's natural to need to connect with people, to effect our means - that being our work - toward that end, and it's also reasonable, and equally natural, to want to keep things simple and uncomplicated. That silence isn't just deafening, it's stultifying, and it creeps in over time, eventually becoming too heavy to bear. You may not need the trappings of a community for validation, but having a circle of friends with the same impetus, goals, and interests will matter more than anything in the long run. Those who wish to write or draw in service to others, whether for purpose, or latitude over others (fame I suppose), or personal gain. I'm grateful for those I've made, though it took time to realize it had even happened.
I'm grappling with my own hang-ups, as we all are. This coming year, I'm gonna move on with my creative goals despite those personal obstacles, though I've come to realize I only really embrace that as an adjunct to moving on in a much broader sense (talkin' life stuff over anything). I'm still figuring out what that entails, but it's an overdue resolution.
Happy New Year, biiiiiitches.
